definition.value: Catalysis of the reactions -  chlorophyllide a + O2 + NADPH + H+ -eq- 7-hydroxychlorophyllide a + H2O + NADP+ -  and 7-hydroxychlorophyllide a + O2 + NADPH + H+ -eq- chlorophyllide b + 2 H2O + NADP+.

The protein transport machinery of the chloroplast outer membrane that contains at least three components Toc159, Toc75 and Toc34, interacts with precursor proteins which are imported into the chloroplast in a GTP dependant manner.
Catalysis of the reaction -  indole-3-acetic acid + an amino acid -eq- an indole-3-acetic acid amide conjugate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-D-glucose + NADPH + H+ -eq- UDP-L-rhamnose + NADP+ + H2O.

A lytic vacuole that is maintained at acidic pH and has different tonoplast composition compared to the central vacuole. Found during leaf senescence and develops in the peripheral cytoplasm of cells that contain chloroplast.
Catalysis of the reaction -  pinoresinol + NADPH + H+ -eq- lariciresinol + NADP+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  lariciresinol + NADPH + H+ -eq- secoisolariciresinol + NADP+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2-oxoglutarate + LL-2,6-diaminopimelate -eq- (S)-2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate + L-glutamate + H(2)O + H(+).

A lipoprotein particle present in chloroplasts. They are rich in non-polar lipids (triglycerides, esters) as well as in prenylquinones, plastoquinone and tocopherols. Plastoglobules are often associated with thylakoid membranes, suggesting an exchange of lipids with thylakoids.
Enables the directed movement of chlorophyll catabolites such as non-fluorescent chlorophyll catabolites (NCCs), from one side of the membrane to the other.

Catalysis of the reaction -  a carotene + a reduced electron acceptor + O2 -eq- C3-hydroxylated carotene + an oxidized electron acceptor + H2O. This is a general reaction to represent the C3 hydroxylation of the beta ring of a carotene.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GTP(out) + GDP(in) -eq- GTP(in) + GDP(out).
Catalysis of the reaction -  (+)-abscisic aldehyde + H(2)O + O(2) -eq- abscisate + H(2)O(2) + H(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  (+)-abscisate + UDP-D-glucose -eq- abscisic acid glucose ester + UDP.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (+)-abscisate + H(+) + NADPH + O(2) -eq- (+)-8'-hydroxyabscisate + H(2)O + NADP(+).
Catalysis of the reaction -  protein C-terminal S-farnesyl-L-cysteine methyl ester + H2O -eq- protein C-terminal S-farnesyl-L-cysteine + methanol + H+.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with heteropolysaccharides. A heteropolysaccharide is a glycan composed of more than one type of monosaccharide residue.
Catalysis of the reaction -  dihydrocamalexic acid -eq- camalexin + CO2 + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NAD(+) + xanthoxin -eq- (+)-abscisic aldehyde + H(+) + NADH.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of (1,6)-alpha-D-glucosidic linkages in alpha- and beta-limit dextrins of amylopectin and glycogen, and in amylopectin and pullulan.
Modulates the enzyme activity of acetylglutamate kinase.
Catalysis of the reaction -  1,2-dihydroxy-5-(methylthio)pent-1-en-3-one + O(2) -eq- 3-(methylthio)propanoate + CO + formate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  1,2-dihydroxy-5-(methylthio)pent-1-en-3-one + O(2) -eq- 4-methylthio-2-oxobutanoate + formate + H(+).
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with phytochrome.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with phosphatidylinositol-5-phosphate, a derivative of phosphatidylinositol in which the inositol ring is phosphorylated at the 5' position.
Heterodimeric complex that catalyzes the pyrophosphate-dependent phosphorylation of D-fructose 6-phosphate into D-fructose 1,6-bisphosphate.
Refers to the alpha subunit of the heterodimeric complex that possesses pyrophosphate-dependent phosphofructokinase activity.
Refers to the beta subunit of the heterodimeric complex that possesses pyrophosphate-dependent phosphofructokinase activity.

Thin filamentous structure extending from the surface of all plastid types examined so far, including chloroplast, proplastid, etioplast, leucoplast, amyloplast, and chromoplast. In general, stromules are more abundant in tissues containing non-green plastids, and in cells containing smaller plastids. The primary function of stromules is still unresolved, although the presence of stromules markedly increases the plastid surface area, potentially increasing transport to and from the cytosol. Other functions of stromules, such as transfer of macromolecules between plastids and starch granule formation in cereal endosperm, may be restricted to particular tissues and cell types.
Catalysis of the reaction -  methionine + a 2-oxo acid -eq- 2-oxo-4-methylthiobutanoate + an amino acid.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + (Z)-3-hexen-1-ol -eq- CoA + (Z)-3-hexen-1-yl acetate.
Catalysis of the transfer of auxin, from one side of a membrane to the other, into a cell.
Catalysis of the transfer of auxin, from one side of a membrane to the other, out of a cell.
A large, multimeric protein complex, organized in a rosette, which catalyzes the biosynthesis of cellulose for the plant cell wall.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with gibberellins, plant hormones that regulate aspects of plant growth.

Catalysis of the formation of cyclic terpenes through the cyclization of linear terpenes (e.g. isopentenyl-PP, geranyl-PP, farnesyl-PP and geranylgeranyl-PP) containing varying numbers of isoprene units.
Catalysis of the reaction -  trans,trans-farnesyl diphosphate -eq- a sesquiterpene + diphosphate. Sesquiterpenes are terpenes containing three isoprene units, i.e. 15 carbons.
The side of the cell wall that is opposite to the side that faces the cell and its contents.
Catalysis of the transfer of a methyl group to the carboxyl group of an acceptor molecule to form a methyl ester.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + a gibberellin -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + a gibberellin methyl ester.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-galactose-1-phosphate + H2O -eq- L-galactose + phosphate.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  Li+(in) + H+(out) -eq- Li+(out) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-galactose + NAD+ -eq- L-galactono-1,4-lactone + NADH + H+.
Catalysis of the transfer of a prenyl group from one compound (donor) to homogentisic acid.
Catalysis of the reaction -  homogentisic acid + farnesyl diphosphate -eq- 2-methyl-6-farnesylplastoquinol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  homogentisic acid + geranylgeranyl diphosphate -eq- 2-methyl-6-geranylgeranylplastoquinol.

Catalysis of the reaction -  homogentisic acid + all-trans-nonaprenyl diphosphate + 3 H+ -eq- 2-methyl-6-solanyl-1,4-benzoquinonone + CO2 + diphosphate. 2-methyl-6-solanyl-1,4-benzoquinonone is also known as 2-methyl-6-solanesylplastoquinol and all-trans-nonaprenyl diphosphate as solanesyl diphosphate.

A protein complex whose composition varies amongst species -  in rice it probably exists in a homo-tetramer to homo-hexamer form and in Gram negative bacteria as a dimer. Functions in the hydrolysis of alpha-(1,6)-D-glucosidic branch linkages. Isoamylases in animals are localized in the extracellular space.

A protein complex whose composition varies amongst species -  in rice it probably exists in a homo-tetramer to homo-hexamer form and in Gram negative bacteria as a dimer. Functions in the hydrolysis of alpha-(1,6)-D-glucosidic branch linkages. Isoamylases in plants are intracellular and probably chloroplast localized.
A region in which centric, heterochromatic portions of one or more chromosomes form a compact structure.
